		   <table class="mform"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform" valign="top">Grouping (higher lvl)<br clear=all>
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Sat, Aug 19th 11:54 AM 2000 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class=sm>IP: Logged</span> | <a href="/db/classes.html?class=8&mid=96670046415446&post=1"><a class=sm href="/db/classes.html?class=8&mid=96670046415446&num=3&post=1&replyto=96670046415446"><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=11 width=17> Reply to this</a></a>   <a name=96670046415446></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=451"><span id=>Cherri</span></a><b><span id=></span></b><br>12 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>Someone mentioned in here somewhere about thorns and why or why not people may or may not want them.&nbsp;&nbsp;There should be no reason why somebody would not want them.  Thorns DOES NOT add to any agro status.  If you want proof of that, thorn a newbie and have them attack something (taunt it or hail it) but don't do any damage to it.  They will not get any experience for the kill, in fact, if the only damage done to the mob is thorn damage, the mob will poof upon dying, as if it killed itself.  Which is actually what it did.  Thorn damage is damage done by the mob itself.  It does not make it any harder to taunt the mob off a thorned caster/cleric (though, until you get Circle of Thorns, I doubt they would be thorned anyway.)  So, please use thorns, and at higher levels, the circle of thorns works wonders.  If the only thing you do as a druid (in a group) is snare, thorn, and buff - you will be considered a good group member.  Personaly, I wish we got an AE snare a lot earlier, but...oh well.<br><br>The ocasional heal is nice - but until Greater heal, it is only as back-up in any serious dungeon.  Anyway, G-heal is only good for a few levels before it, too, becomes lame and you strive to get to 53 so you can fizzle Superior heal and figure out that you better stick to G-heal till you get to level 54.<br><br>On a side note, our DD's do not suck, they rock for our class, we are a priest class, and we deal the most damage for that class.<br>Example:<br>Druid (lvl 54 - Scoriae) 688 dmg for 250 mana at 4 sec cast.<br>Wizard (lvl 51 - Draught of Fire) 688 dmg for 215 mana at 3 sec cast.<br>AND WE CAN HEAL TOO! So, that is a pretty good example how we stack up against others.  Obviously, Clerics heal best + anti-undead, Shamens buff and debuff + heal.  We deal damage + heal.  Be it direct (DDs, DOTs) or indirect (Thorns) that is what we do.  In my experience, Druids are added to groups as an offensive power with healing abilities.  In groups, DOTs are less effective because most mobs die before the DOT finishes, so stick to the DDs.<br><br>I hope this helps a bit, it is geared for higher level, but I believe that it is still good "food for thought"  Post your comments, please.  The Druid strategy guide has been the most lively guide so far, good discussion will help us all make it better.  Since nobody knows everything, keep posting, this guide rocks!  Keep it going!</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >3 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
